{{unreferenced|date=November 2012}}

'''Emilia''' ({{lang-egl|Emîlia}}) is a historical region of northern [[Italy]] which approximately corresponds to the western and north-eastern portions of today’s [[Emilia-Romagna]] [[Regions of Italy|region]], of which [[Romagna]] forms the remainder.

==Etymology==
It takes its name from the [[Via Aemilia]], a [[Roman road]] constructed by the [[consul]] [[Marcus Aemilius Lepidus (consul 187 BC)|Marcus Aemilius Lepidus]] in 187 BCE to connect [[Rimini]] with [[Piacenza]].

==Boundaries==
The eastern boundary is formed by the rivers [[Sillaro]] and [[Reno (river)|Reno]], which divide it from [[Romagna]]. To the north the river [[Po (river)|Po]] forms its border with [[Veneto]] and [[Lombardy]]. To the west and south the [[Apennine Mountains|Apennine]] [[drainage divide]] separates it from [[Liguria]] and [[Tuscany]]. Administratively it comprises the [[Provinces of Italy|provinces]] of [[Piacenza (province)|Piacenza]], [[Parma (province)|Parma]], [[Reggio Emilia (province)|Reggio Emilia]], [[Modena (province)|Modena]], [[Bologna (province)|Bologna]] (except for the [[comuni|communes]] of [[Imola]] and [[Dozza]], and the valley of the [[Santerno]]) and [[Ferrara (province)|Ferrara]].

The region corresponds approximately to the ancient [[Cisalpine Gaul|Cispadane Gaul]] which, under the [[Augustus|Augustan]] [[Italia (Roman Empire)#Under the Republic and Augustan organization|territorial organisation]] of [[Italia]] c. 7 CE, became [[Regio VIII Aemilia]].

==Language==
{{See also|Italian language|Emilian language}}

Although [[Italian language|Italian]] is today the most widely, it is the [[Emilian language|Emilian dialect]] which is specific to the region, although it is spoken in hybrid form in neighbouring provinces.

