'''France Planina''' (29 September 1901 – 14 January 1992) was a [[Slovenes|Slovene]] [[geographer]] and  [[Cartography|cartographer]].<ref>[http://www.mdloka.si/slo/main.asp?id=29622A7F Škofja Loka Museum Society site]</ref>

Planina was born in [[Škofja Loka]] in 1901. He graduated from the [[University of Ljubljana]] in 1925 and taught in secondary schools in [[Otočac]], [[Kranj]] and [[Ljubljana]]. During the [[Second World War]] he was interred in the [[Gonars concentration camp]]. After the war he continued to teach and also worked at the [[Natural History Museum of Slovenia]]. He retired in 1962.<ref>[http://www.gorenjci.si/osebe/planina-france/17/ Web Biographical Lexicon of Famous People from Upper Carniola]</ref> He died in Ljubljana in 1992. In 2001 a bronze [[Bust (sculpture)|bust]] to Planina was unveiled in Škofja Loka.<ref>[http://www.skofjaloka.si/default.aspx?Tip=1551651&KeyID=68&Naslov=Aleja_znamenitih_Locanov Škofja Loka Municipality site, Monuments to Famous Locals]</ref>

In 1967 he won the [[Levstik Award]] for his book ''Jugoslavija'' (Yugoslavia).<ref>[http://www.mladinska.com/knjige/knjizne_nagrade/levstikove__nagrade The Levstik Award on the Mladinska Knjiga Publishing House site]</ref>

