[[File:La Rampa - La Habana, 1950s.jpg|thumb|300px|right|La Rampa - La Habana, 1950s]]
'''La Rampa''' (also known as Calle 23) is a street in the [[Vedado]] district of [[Havana]], [[Cuba]].

La Rampa runs from the [[Malecón, Havana|Malecón]] to Calle L, and passes by airline offices, cinemas, nightclubs, and office buildings. La Rampa, which means “the slope” in Spanish, is the last stretch of the famous Calle 23, leading up to the center of [[Vedado]]. Built in 1930, the location previously was used for a battery of canons that protected the city from attack. In the 1950s, this was the area where many of the city's highest buildings were built, including Someillán and the Mountain Lopez. Many hotels, clubs and shops also crowded along this stretch, such as [[Hotel Tryp Habana Libre|Habana Libre]], the former site of the Hilton Hotel, the [[Hotel Capri]] and the [[Hotel Nacional]]. The country’s most famous ice cream shop [[Coppelia (ice cream parlor)|Coppelia]] is also close to the street.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.havanainsider.com/la-rampa/|title=La Rampa|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref> On the corner of 23rd and L is the [[Radiocentro CMQ Building]] and further down the block is the [[Edificio del Seguro Médico, Havana|Edificio del Seguro Médico]] by Antonio Quintana.
