[[File:Salt_lake_city_base_and_meridian.jpg|thumb|The Great Salt Lake Base and Meridian]] The '''Salt Lake meridian''', established in 1855, in longitude 111° 54′ 00″ west from Greenwich, has its initial point at southeast corner of [[Temple Square]], in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]], extends north and south through the state, and, with the base line, through the initial, and coincident with the parallel of 40° 46′ 04″ north latitude, governs the surveys in the territory, except those referred to the [[Uintah meridian]] and Baseline projected from an initial point in latitude 40° 26′ 20″ north, longitude 109° 57′ 30″ west from Greenwich.
